 are leading mathematicians who have also been highly influential as teachers and mentors, like Tom Apostol and Jean Taylor. Fern Hunt describes what it was like to be among the first black women to earn a PhD in mathematics. Harold Bacon made trips to Alcatraz to help a prisoner learn calculus. Thomas Banchoff, who first became interested in the fourth dimension while reading a Captain Marvel comic, relates his fascinating friendship with Salvador Dalí and their shared passion for art, mathematics, and the profound connection between the two. Other mathematical people found here are Leon Bankoff, who was also a Beverly Hills dentist; Arthur Benjamin, a part-time professional magician; and Joseph Gallian, a legendary mentor of future mathematicians, but also a world-renowned expert on the Beatles. This beautifully illustrated collection includes many photographs never before published, concise introductions by the editors to each person, and a foreword by Philip J. Davis.Some images inside the book are unavailable due to digital copyright restrictions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMathematiciansvBiography. 0aMathematiciansvInterviews. 0aMathématiciensvBiographies. 0aMathématiciensvEntretiens. 7aMATHEMATICS / Essays.2bisacsh1 aAlbers, Donald J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbers, Donald J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlexanderson, Gerald L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexanderson, Gerald L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavis, Philip J.1 aDavis, Philip J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaunsperger, Deanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenrion, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4http